{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff: taxonomy can be correct in local constants but dropped/partial in the outbound payload. A pure unit of label-list construction can miss wiring bugs. Higher levels are not required because behavior text is about request shape, not real network behavior or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire the classifier with a stub API client that records outbound request bodies. Invoke classify(document) and assert the request contains exactly the full configured taxonomy labels (no missing/extra labels).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is local validation/mapping logic: out-of-taxonomy input must map to \"unknown\". This can be exposed with a deterministic function/object test and no real I/O. Rejected Integration because behavior text does not require real module wiring beyond supplying an invalid label value.","test_description":"Test the classifier’s response-mapping logic with an injected invalid label (e.g., \"medical\") and assert returned value is \"unknown\". Keep API interaction mocked/stubbed to focus on mapping rule.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration was considered but rejected: behavior targets mapping outcome for an invalid label value, which is local logic." ,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.55,"Integration":0.4,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model output stability across repeated invocations. Stubbed/deterministic responses would always pass and hide true nondeterminism. Workflow is not needed because this is a single agentic step repeated, not a multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Call the real AI classification API multiple times (e.g., N repeated calls) for the same document under same settings; assert label consistency criterion (exact match or predefined stability threshold). Record run-to-run variance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real external API/token-accounting behavior (actual consumed tokens), which in-process fakes can misrepresent. This does not primarily depend on semantic quality of model output, so Agentic is not strictly required. Rejected lower levels because mocked usage counters can always satisfy budget while production accounting exceeds it.","test_description":"Run classification against the real API for representative document(s), read authoritative usage/token metrics from API response/billing fields, and assert consumed tokens <= configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic considered but rejected: behavior is token-usage enforcement, not output-quality judgment." ,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.55,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is retry orchestration across modules (API client error -> backoff/wait -> retry -> success). This is catchable with in-process stubs/fake clock; real OS/network/subprocess is not required. Rejected System because behavior text only requires handling a signaled rate-limit response, not real network conditions.","test_description":"Use a stub client scripted to return rate-limit error first, then success. Verify classifier performs wait/backoff (with fake clock or bounded real sleep), retries expected number of times, and returns final success result instead of surfacing initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
